rporate networks I&#8217;ve come across. It puts a bunch of ideas I&#8217;v=
e been writing about into production.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 6=
4, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Let me tak=
e a step back, though. Starting with a couple questions you might be asking=
: what is Farcaster and what are Frames?&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64=
, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>F=
arcaster is a </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/b7d22956-a297=
-41fa-9cce-57a2409326bb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: unde=
rline;">sufficiently decentralized social network</a><span> founded by Dan =
Romero and Varun Srinivasan.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64,=
 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Farcas=
ter is a </span><strong>protocol</strong><span>, responsible for storing th=
ings like user&#8217;s handles, casts (Farcaster&#8217;s version of tweets)=
, and reactions (like likes and recasts).&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color=
: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
><span>Anyone can build their own </span><strong>clients</strong><span> on =
top of Farcaster that use that data but offer different frontend experience=
s.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Clients are interfaces through which u=
sers access the feed. We don&#8217;t use that word &#8220;client&#8221; muc=
h anymore, because in most modern social networks, like Twitter and Faceboo=
k, the protocol and the client are the same thing. Twitter used to have cli=
ents, like Tweetdeck and Twitterific, until it shut down its API access and=
 killed the clients. Now, Twitter is just Twitter (or, if you prefer, X).&#=
160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 2=
6px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">You can think of Farcaster as a Twitter that&#821=
7;s extensible by its community and always will be.&#160;</p><p style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px =
0;"><span>The Farcaster team built its own </span><strong>client</strong><s=
pan>, </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/c7e4c275-76b1-4668-98=
55-381691ac00a8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">=
Warpcast</a><span>, but any developer is free and encouraged to create thei=
r own competing client. Many have. a16z crypto has a list of General and Sp=
ecialized clients in their </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/=
7208c8ea-de2b-4a23-9b1b-5dd697ab9f3d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-dec=
oration: underline;">awesome-farcaster repo</a><span>, including Supercast,=
 Yup, Searchcaster, Launchcaster, Eventcaster, and Casthose. Each takes a d=
ifferent twist to the frontend experience of accessing Farcaster&#8217;s da=
ta and interacting with its users.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(6=
4, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>=
A few months ago, the Farcaster team introduced </span><strong>channels</st=
rong><span> as a way to organize conversations by topic. The Farcaster team=
 created the first few channels, and then opened up the ability to create n=
ew channels to any user. Once created, those channels show up in any client=
 that chooses to build them in, with all of the same casts you&#8217;d see =
in Warpcast.&#160;&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>And on Friday, F=
arcaster launched </span><strong>Frames</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">Frames let people build small apps that run inside of casts.=
&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height:=
 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">They&#8217;re essentially small, interactive if=
rames embedded in casts, hence the name. Like casts, handles, and channels,=
 Frames work in any Farcaster client.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 6=
4, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Frames can=
 support anything from Doom to polls to block explorers to mints to buys to=
 prediction markets.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size=
: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Frames are just a canvas; d=
evelopers will figure out what to paint on them.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color=
: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
>And they are! In the four days since launch, developers have built Frames =
that let users mint songs in one click, subscribe to a newsletter in one cl=
ick, and play games right in their feed, including Doom.&#160;</p><div clas=
