e=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 20px 0;">More experimentation is a good thing for its own sake. Novelty i=
s the feedstock of progress. And experimentation is good for the platforms =
that enable it.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Ben Thompson explained it =
in a way that has stuck with me in </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.c=
om/redirect/36e6007b-9f82-4f0c-8e2f-0d6bebc5ce33?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 6=
4); text-decoration: underline;">Shopify and the Power of Platforms</a></em=
><span>:&#160;</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #51b4e=
9; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><s=
pan>I would argue that for Shopify </span><strong>a high churn rate is just=
 as much a positive signal as it is a negative one</strong><span>: the easi=
er it is to start an e-commerce business on the platform, the more failures=
 there will be. And, at the same time, the greater likelihood there will be=
 of capturing and supporting successes.</span></em></p></blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 20px 0;"><span>The easier it is to experiment on a platform, the more fai=
lures </span><em>and </em><span>successes there will be, and the greater th=
e likelihood the platform itself will win.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">I&#8217;m going to include a long block quote here, which Dan will hate, =
because I think Ben says it so well (emphasis mine):&#160;</p><blockquote s=
tyle=3D"border-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>What is powerful about this model =
is that it leverages the best parts of modularity &#8212; diversity and com=
petition at different parts of the value chain &#8212; and aligns the incen=
tives of all of them. Every referral partner, developer, theme designer, an=
d now 3PL provider is </span><strong>simultaneously incentivized to compete=
 with each other narrowly and ensure that Shopify succeeds broadly, because=
 that means the pie is bigger for everyone.</strong></em></p><p style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px =
0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>This is the only way to take on an integrated Ag=
gregator like Amazon: trying to replicate what Amazon has built up over dec=
ades, as Walmart has attempted, is madness. Amazon has the advantage in eve=
ry part of the stack, from more customers to more suppliers to lower fulfil=
lment costs to faster delivery.</em></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;=
"><em><strong>The only way out of that competition is differentiation</stro=
ng><span>; granted, Walmart has tried buying and launching new brands exclu=
sive to its store, but differentiation when it comes to e-commerce goods do=
esn&#8217;t arise from top down planning. </span><strong>Rather, it bubbles=
 up from widespread opportunity (and churn!), like that created by Shopify,=
 supported by an entire aligned ecosystem.</strong></em></p></blockquote><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;">You can find and replace &#8220;Amazon&#8221; with &#8220;T=
witter,&#8221; &#8220;Walmart&#8221; with &#8220;Threads,&#8221; and &#8220=
;Shopify&#8221; with &#8220;Farcaster&#8221; and the argument works just as=
 well.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>(I&#8217;m not trying to make the e=
commerce analogy directly, but interestingly, Alex Danco, who works on </sp=
an><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/9196c2c8-5969-4aba-bf3c-6589c53=
402c0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" r=
el style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">making Sho=
pify wallet aware</a><span>, </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirec=
t/2d3efb8b-9d7e-4a4c-a467-28b19b9e0335?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-d=
ecoration: underline;">tweeted</a><span>: &#8220;frames are a key missing p=
iece of ecommerce infra that now suddenly works.&#8221; This thing has leve=
ls.)</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">By enabling widespread opportunity and enc=
ouraging competition (for attention) and churn at the experimentation layer=
, and building an aligned ecosystem of developers who benefit from a larger=
 and more engaged community of users, Farcaster has the opportunity to buil=
d differentiated social infrastructure and succeed where other Twitter comp=
etitors have failed.&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=
=3D"-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialias=
